'''Bradley Moore Davis''' (1871-1957) was an [[United States|American]] [[botany|botanist]], born in [[Chicago]].  After graduating from [[Stanford University|Leland Stanford Junior University]], in [[1892]], he studied at [[Harvard University|Harvard]], [[Bonn]], and [[Naples]].  For 11 years he taught at the [[University of Chicago]], from [[1902]] to [[1906]] as assistant professor of plant morphology.  He held a position at the [[Marine Biological Laboratory]], [[Woods Hole, Massachusetts|Woods Hole]], [[Massachusetts|Mass.]] ([[1897]]-[[1905]]) and at the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|Bureau of Fisheries]].  In [[1911]] he became assistant professor of botany at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and  he was secretary of the [[American Society of Naturalists]] in [[1914]].  Besides special articles on the morphology and [[Cell biology|cytology]] of [[algae|alg<U+00E6>,]] [[fungus|fungi]], and [[Marchantiophyta|liverwort]]s, and studies in the [[Oenothera|<U+0152>nothera]], he was coauthor with [[Joseph Young Bergen|J. Y. Bergen]] of ''Principles of Botany'' (1906) and ''Laboratory and Field Manual of Botany'' (1907).  

  
